## Test naming and structure

```python
# unit
def test_idempotency_returns_cached_response_when_key_reused(): ...

# contract
def test_ihms_place_hold_request_matches_expected_json_shape(): ...

# component
async def test_saga_compensates_when_ecops_returns_500(): ...

# integration
async def test_post_confirm_returns_201_with_order_id(): ...

# e2e
@pytest.mark.e2e
async def test_full_checkout_happy_path(): ...
```

Use descriptive names. One logical assertion cluster per test.

---

## Mocking guidelines

| Layer | Mock |
|-------|------|
| unit | Mock everything external |
| contract | Mock transport; assert wire format |
| component | Mock gateway module boundary |
| integration | Mock gateway OR use respx/httpx mock |
| e2e | Real services in compose |

Prefer mocking at **gateway boundary** over mocking httpx deep inside saga.

---

## Quality gate before PR

- [ ] `bash scripts/verify.sh` green
- [ ] New code has appropriate test tier
- [ ] FAILURE-SCENARIOS row covered if flow changed
- [ ] Saga compensation path tested for any new write to EC-OPS
- [ ] Idempotency tested for confirm
- [ ] PERFORMANCE.md updated if timeout/retry changed
- [ ] No `@pytest.mark.e2e` tests run in default verify (unless STACK=1)

---

## Anti-patterns

- Skipping component tier ("integration is enough")
- Testing saga logic only through HTTP — also unit test steps
- Blind retry on POST /orders without idempotency key
- Asserting exact UUID values — assert presence/format instead
- Real calls to IHMS/EC-OPS in unit/contract/component/integration tests

